Approach 1: CUI Extraction from Everything
User Query
    │
    ▼
Nature Breakdown
    │   intents → sub-natures → atomic concepts
    │   context retrieval (5 dims) on each atomic concept
    │
    ▼
CUI Extraction (from 3 sources)
    │   atomic concept text → CUIs
    │   sub-nature category paths → CUIs
    │   nature strings → CUIs
    │
    ▼
Merged CUI Pool
    │   mixed CUIs from all 3 source types
    │
    ▼
Summarizer
    │
    ▼
Topic Formation
    │
    ▼
Enrichment with Context Retrieval (broken)
    │   atomic-concept CUIs → have 5 context dims
    │   sub-nature CUIs → no context retrieval (orphans)
    │   nature CUIs → no context retrieval (orphans)
    │   consolidation is incomplete or fabricated
    │
    │   per topic, attach:
    │     - document_types (partial union)
    │     - author_roles (partial union)
    │     - temporal_signals (partial union)
    │     - content_signals (partial union)
    │     - clinical_setting (partial union)
    │     - sub_nature_paths (multiple)
    │     - intent_ids (possibly multiple)
    │
    ▼
Search Adapter Cascade
    Stage 0: section scoping using document_types 
             (incoherent due to partial consolidation)
    Stage 1: embedding similarity
    Stage 2: sub-topic CUI matching
    Stage 3: ranking using author_roles, temporal_signals, 
             content_signals, clinical_setting
             (same incoherence problem)
    │
    ▼
Combiner
Problem: Sub-nature and nature CUIs have no native context retrieval. Enrichment breaks for those orphan CUIs, so the consolidated 5 dimensions are partial or fabricated. Every cascade stage inherits that incoherence.

Approach 2: Merged Pool with Source Tagging
User Query
    │
    ▼
Nature Breakdown
    │   intents → sub-natures → atomic concepts
    │   context retrieval (5 dims) on each atomic concept
    │
    ▼
CUI Extraction (atomic concepts only)
    │   each CUI tagged with source atomic concept ID
    │
    ▼
Merged CUI Pool
    │   source tags attached to every CUI
    │
    ▼
Summarizer
    │   source tags preserved through reduction
    │
    ▼
Topic Formation
    │   topics inherit source tags from constituent CUIs
    │   topics may span sub-natures and intents
    │
    ▼
Enrichment with Context Retrieval via Source Tag Lookup
    │   for each topic, look up source atomic concepts via tags
    │   union the 5 context dimensions across ALL contributing 
    │   atomic concepts (global union)
    │
    │   per topic, attach:
    │     - document_types (broad union across sub-natures)
    │     - author_roles (broad union across sub-natures)
    │     - temporal_signals (broad union)
    │     - content_signals (broad union)
    │     - clinical_setting (broad union)
    │     - sub_nature_paths (multiple possible)
    │     - intent_ids (multiple possible)
    │
    ▼
Search Adapter Cascade
    Stage 0: section scoping using document_types 
             (broad → less precise)
    Stage 1: embedding similarity
    Stage 2: sub-topic CUI matching
    Stage 3: ranking using author_roles, temporal_signals, 
             content_signals, clinical_setting
             (broad unions → diluted ranking signal)
    │
    ▼
Combiner
    │   has to handle cross-sub-nature topics
    │   has to handle cross-intent topics
Problem: Topics can span sub-natures and intents. Context retrieval consolidation is broad because unions cross dimensional boundaries. Stage 0 scoping casts a wide net. Stage 3 ranking signals are diluted because they union across unrelated atomic concepts.

Approach 3: Sub-Nature as Query Topic (Recommended)
User Query
    │
    ▼
Nature Breakdown
    │   intents → sub-natures → atomic concepts
    │   context retrieval (5 dims) on each atomic concept
    │
    ▼
CUI Extraction (atomic concepts only)
    │   no source tagging needed
    │
    ▼
Aggregation by Sub-Nature
    │   for each sub-nature:
    │     collect CUIs from its atomic concepts
    │     compute average embedding from those CUIs
    │     the sub-nature IS a query topic
    │
    ▼
Direct Enrichment with Context Retrieval
    │   for each topic (= sub-nature):
    │     - cuis (from its atomic concepts)
    │     - avg embedding
    │     - sub_nature_path (single value)
    │     - intent_id (single value)
    │     - nature (from parent intent)
    │   
    │   5 context dimensions, unioned across atomic 
    │   concepts under THIS sub-nature only:
    │     - document_types (tight union, clinically coherent)
    │     - author_roles (tight union)
    │     - temporal_signals (tight union)
    │     - content_signals (tight union)
    │     - clinical_setting (tight union)
    │
    ▼
Search Adapter Cascade
    Stage 0: section scoping using document_types 
             (tight → sharper scoping)
    Stage 1: embedding similarity
    Stage 2: sub-topic CUI matching
    Stage 3: ranking using author_roles, temporal_signals, 
             content_signals, clinical_setting
             (tight unions → clearer ranking signal)
    │
    ▼
Combiner
    │   trivial: one intent and one sub-nature per topic
Why recommended: Every atomic concept under a sub-nature contributes cleanly. All 5 context dimensions are unioned within a small, clinically coherent set. Every cascade stage gets sharper scoping and ranking signals because the consolidated context retrieval isn't diluted by cross-sub-nature mixing.
